 and turn north on the interstate towards Montreal, and then to Ottawa.  <br>
<br>
We wanna leave Friday night at about 6pm here in Toronto, and hopefully get past Rochester and then sleep somewhere in a motel.  Then on Saturday we want to drive and drive and perhaps get to Montreal, spend the night and morning there, and then head to Ottawa.  Spend the rest of the day there, sleep over with some family, and then come back.<br>
<br>
How does that sound?  Any recommendations?  Any must do's and must not do's?  Any advice appreciated... <p>&quot;thanks for the usage babe. *kiss*&quot; --Kazzap Kaboom<br>
-- Smartypus blushes...</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=murel>Murel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 1731<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/25/03 7:44 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Planning a road trip</span><hr size=1> Don't drive tired, don't rush, take your time, stretch your legs, refresh yourself on occasion. Basic stuff is all I can think of. Have fun <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eaminwhitefalcon@graffeswizardcompilation>Eamin Whitefalcon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>¡Viva la inquisición!</span><br>  Posts: 7479<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/25/03 8:08 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Planning a road trip</span><hr size=1> SWITCH DRIVERS. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=llith>Llith</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 1075<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/25/03 9:17 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Planning a road trip</span><hr size=1> If you've been driving for a while and want to keep going do NOT eat. Drink loads of soda and maybe a candy bar but if you eat after you've been driving for 8 hours it will put you to sleep. I make tons of short trips by myself and thats the one most important thing i've learned. <p>Sorceress of the Rathe<br>
<br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=aurianne>Aurianne</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 3758<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/25/03 9:38 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Planning a road trip</span><hr size=1> When you get to Ottawa, you must give me a call, sir. I'll IM you the phone number tomorrow <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I'm working on Canada Day from noon to 8pm, but can go out for partying afterwards... I work downtown, literally 2 blocks from Parliament Hill....<br>
<br>
<br>
As for your trip, have a good time. Change drivers when you start to feel tired. Frequent rest stops. Get out of the car and walk around, if even for 5 minutes, every few hours. It'll add maybe an hour to your trip, but you'll arrive and not feel completely wasted. Oh, and it's better to pull over and check into a motel than it is to keep driving the night through. When you start to feel fatigued, stop. Most accidents happen when people are fatigued. Oh, and invest in travel insurance. You probably won't need it, but you'll be happy you spent the extra $20 if you do need it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<br>Err, Forum Arch Mage?</span><br>  Posts: 4904<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/26/03 12:45 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Planning a road trip</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>and then turn east to that big park. Pass through that<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Only thing I can remember about the Adirondak Park at the moment is that the roads can be winding and are almost all 2-lane with no passing.  It's not like driving on cliffs or anything but you <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>are</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> driving through a mountain range.  Traffic can slow you down a lot, especially if you plan on going through more popular places such as Old Forge.  Route 28 south of Old Forge I remember as being particularly troublesome.  North of there things would clear up a bit.<br>
<br>
I haven't been up there in years though...  so I really couldn't suggest any routes to take or sites to visit.  Most people go up there for hiking/boating/etc.  At this time of year it should be fairly cool and the air should be fresh. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dynamiteshortfuze>Dynamite Shortfuze</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 545<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/26/03 6:18 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Planning a road trip</span><hr size=1> You'll find that Ottawa has shawarma places as frequently as the rest of the world has McDonald's. Ottawa has a population of 1 million, and 300 thousand of them are Lebanese. If you want the best shawarma Ottawa has to offer, go to Marroush on Elgin St. Anyone downtown can tell you how to get there.<br>
<br>
Also, while there, touristy things to do are tour the Parliament buildings, the mint (yes, the money one), any of the museums (war museum, art museum, photography museum.....), and take a boat tour down the Rideau Canal.<br>
<br>
In Montreal, have a smoked meat sandwich. There's no option here. If you're in Montreal, you're eating smoked meat. Montreal also has one of the best night scenes you'll encounter... lots of fun no matter where you go. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=apollohades>Apollohades</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 222<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/26/03 7:31 am)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Planning a road trip</span><hr size=1> I just got back from Montreal and the food didn't impress me.<br>
